Halve the @bell pepper{1} and discard the core and seeds. Slice into thin strips. Trim and thinly slice the @spring onion{1}. Halve, peel and thinly slice the @onion{1}. Heat a large #frying pan{} on medium heat (no oil). Once hot, add the @sesame seeds{15} and dry-fry, stirring regularly, until lightly toasted, ~{2-3%minutes}.

> Watch them like a hawk as they can burn easily.

Transfer them to a #small bowl{}.

Pop the (now empty) frying pan back on medium-high heat. Add the @sesame oil{24%g}. When hot, add the sliced pepper and onion and stir-fry until soft and starting to char, ~{6-7%minutes}. Once charred, add the @ginger puree{1} then remove from the heat.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a #medium frying pan{} on high heat. When the oil is hot, add the @British beef mince{240%g} and cook until browned, ~{5-6%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw mince.

Use a #wooden spoon{} to break it up as it cooks. Drain and discard any excess fat from the beef, then season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Once cooked, add half of the @Szechuan paste{100%g} and set the pan aside.

> The mince is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Meanwhile, bring a #saucepan{} of water up to the boil with 1/4 tsp @salt{1/4%tsp} for the noodles. When boiling, add the @egg noodle nest{2} and cook until tender, ~{4%minutes}. Drain in a #sieve{}.

> Run the noodles under cold water to stop them sticking together.

Once the noodles have cooked, add them to the pan with the beef along with the charred veg and remaining Szechuan paste. Stir well to coat and heat until piping hot.

Share the Szechuan fried beef noodles between your plates. Sprinkle over the spring onion and sesame seeds to finish. Enjoy!